title: For Sale:  Rock River Arms precision with Leupold Mark 4 LR/T
postcontent: I am selling my precision varmint rifle. Everyone always talks about how much a tack driver their gun is, so I will save you the talk. I will say that this rifle set up has far more potential than most shooters abilities will ever realize. The lower is a BMG Raptor gen 2 billet made to the most exacting tolerances, they incorporate a lot of ergonomic upgrades in these lowers but the real advantage to having it is the tight tolerances for setting the trigger group and lock up to the upper receiver. There is no play or slop in this system. The trigger is a JP competition trigger single stage set at around 3 pounds with no creep. Upper is a Rock River Arms Predator Pursuit 16 inch stainless barrel with a 1 in 8 twist Wilde chamber, and mid length gas system. Free floated hand guard is ceracoated in Magpul FDE. Front sight is a YHM HK type integrated gas block sight with Picatinny rail section at bottom. The bolt carrier group is a Rainier Arms, and the charge handle is the Bravo Company long handle for ease of charging with a scope on. Rear sight is a Magpul gen 2 in FDE. Grip is an Ergo Tactical Deluxe Sure Grip in FDE. Stock is a Magpul CTR with friction lock and a single point sling HK type rear plate. The Bipod is a Harris swivel type with notched legs. Scope is a Leupold Mark 4 M1 Reticle 8.5-25X50; http://www.leupold.com/tactical/scopes/mark-4-lrt-riflescopes/mark-4-lrt-8-5-25x50mm-30mm-m1/ It is mounted on a Burris P.E.P.E.R. mount, torqued properly per Leopold's instructions. Also included on the scope is a scope level, extended sun shade, and Butler Creek flip covers. It all fits in the padded case pictured which has a muzzle protector built into the end, durable nylon construction with carry handle and strap, 3 Velcro mag pouches and a forward zippered accessory compartment. I have the 5 round mag that is in it as well as 3 Magpul 30 rounders couple in FDE and one in black. This gun is built ground up with the best stuff and is amazingly accurate, compact, and fast. I will sell the gun and scope combo for $2500, or the scope with accessories and mount for $1000, and the gun alone for $1500. Let me know if interested. Thanks.

title: For Sale:  1942 Gevar M38 Swedish Mauser by Husqvarna
postcontent: This is a gorgeous Gevar M38 Swedish Mauser made by Husqvarna. As you can see from the pics, she is in beautiful condition!As you can see, the muzzle is threaded. They were threaded for a blank firing adapter. The Swedes had blanks that had a wooden bullet. The adapter shredded the wooden bullet. Initially they just told the troops not to aim directly at each other when they were up close, but as a fellow vet you can guess how well that worked.The Gevär m/96-38 proved so successful that when new rifles were ordered for the military in 1941, the contract issued to Husqvarna specified that the new rifle be built to the same pattern. In all, 60,000 new rifles with the 24.5 inch barrel were built at the Husqvarna factory between 1942 and 1945. They can be identified primarily by the marking and date on the receiver-HUSQVARNA VAPENFABRIKS AKTIEBOLAG and a date between 1942 and 1944.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Mossberg Maverick 91 with 590A1 barrel and Remington Tactical Choke
postcontent:
Lowered price. Make me an offer.

It is with much chagrin that I am parting ways with my beloved 91. The Maverick is Mossberg's 'value' line of firearms, made from the exact same components as their popular 500 & 835 counterparts, but with subtle differences like a cross-bolt safety instead of tang safety, as a way to keep costs down. The model 91 is based on the 835, which means it has the ability to fire 3-1/2" magnum shells. 

This particular 91 has an Accu-Mag barrel that measures 28 inches from tip to receiver and comes with 2 chokes, which are Full and I think I/C.

It also comes with a 20" barrel from a 590A1 that has been machined to accept Remington choke tubes, and has a Remington Tactical Choke. I bought this barrel primarily for slug hunting whitetail deer, but it also works quite well as a home defense setup.

I have a random assortment of 12ga ammo that I'll throw in because I don't have any other shotguns. There are some slugs, some buckshot, some birdshot. No I'm not going to tally it up or post a quantity, as far as I'm concerned these are bonus material not included in the price.

In case you're wondering why I'm selling this setup: I don't bird hunt anymore. Got rid of all my decoys a couple years ago. I just picked up the slug barrel earlier this year, but I've decided to instead use a pistol for deer hunting. The funds from this sale will be going towards procuring a 357 or 44 revolver that purpose.

I do believe the price to be extremely fair. Gunsamerica.com recently sold a 91 for $275. The 590 barrel was $200, the Rem choke was $40, and the I/C choke was $25. That's a total value of $540, not counting tax.

Rugged. Reliable. Uncomplicated. The Model 99 is designed for one thing only: to get the job done. With its brilliantly simple design, hard-core construction and surprisingly few moving parts, it offers match-winning accuracy time and time again.

At the heart of this robust and accurate bolt action rifle is a one-piece 7000 series aluminum alloy extrusion. A heat-treated steel M1913 optics rail is attached to the top of the extrusion by closely spaced high-strength bolts. The match-toleranced barrel is pressed and locked into the receiver, creating a rock-solid unitized structure on which to mount a riflescope. The chamber area is encased by the thick-walled aluminum extrusion of the receiver, resulting in unparalleled safety for the shooter.

The bolt is machined from a single piece of shock-resistant tool steel. The action’s strength is exemplified by the 15 bolt lugs that lock into the machined barrel extension. The bolt’s few moving parts, an extractor, ejector and firing pin assembly, make it reliable and easy to maintain.

The Model 99 is easily disassembled without tools by removing three quick-release assembly pins. These pins attach the trigger housing and bolt guide to the receiver assembly. Known as much for its dependability as its versatility, the Model 99 combines smooth functionality with dead-on accuracy, shot after shot.
